Ia$) or field voltage. When the motor reaches its maximum speed, it functions at its base speed. If the speed is less than the base speed, the armature voltage control can be used. If the speed exceeds the base speed, the field current can be changed. The torque generated during overspeed operation is reduced since the motor's output power cannot exceed its nominal value. As a result, the purpose of this study is to examine the advantages and disadvantages of field control and armature control when controlling the speed of a separately excited DC motor.

